==<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Untitled205 20240925204431.png|30px|link=]]</span> Description==
{{Blurimage|file=Fromcomments2.webp|caption=<span style="font-family: Anuphan;">'''Level 61's''' train station.</span>}}
<p style="line-height:160%;">The physical appearance of '''Level 61''' constitutes a series of interconnected vintage train carriages, with a pattern of leather seating separated by an aisle, square windows on both sides, and rows of electric lightbulbs providing light to each carriage. The entirety of '''Level 61''' largely moves forward at a steady pace, similarly to a typical train within the [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]]; however, the train itself is capable of decreasing or increasing speed at random intervals, making navigation throughout '''Level 61''' unpredictable.
</p>

<p style="line-height:160%;">When one first enters '''Level 61''', they will be transported into a peculiar area of the level resembling a traditional locomotive. At the front of the locomotive is a control panel with a number of switches and buttons, though it does not seem to affect the movement or direction that the train travels, or anything at all. Adjacent to the panel is a shaft seemingly for coal, although the door is unable to be opened. Behind the control panel is a door allowing access into the rest of '''Level 61'''. Upon exiting the locomotive, it will disappear and be replaced by more of '''Level 61's''' carriages. There are currently no reports of individuals regaining access after exiting the locomotive.</p>

<p style="line-height:160%;">Despite initial external observation, outside the train carriages of '''Level 61''' is an endless tunnel, seemingly constructed out of stone and clay. Beside the train lies a second track running in the opposite direction. Surrounding the train is a boundless milky white fog, swirling in distinct patterns and shapes. Doors allowing access to the outside of the train are locked from the inside but are able to be destroyed via a degree of force. Open windows also provide outside access. However, it is unrecommended to exit the train, as when one steps out of the train and into the outside, they are never seen again, seemingly consumed by the milky white fog.</p>
{{Blurimage|file=Fromcomments1.webp|caption=<span style="font-family: Anuphan;">An image of '''Level 61's''' restaurant train car.</span>}}
<p style="line-height:160%;">It is possible to encounter a particular train car within '''Level 61''' resembling a typical restaurant area. Circular tables line both sides of the car and are separated by an aisle in the middle. Each table is adorned with an ornate tablecloth and an additional cloth surrounding a flowerpot in the center. Additionally, an arrangement of cutlery and porcelain plating corresponds to four leather chairs surrounding the table. Similar to the entrance locomotive, exiting the restaurant car causes it to disappear and be replaced by more of '''Level 61's''' train cars, though it is able to be accessed again after a certain distance.</p>

<p style="line-height:160%;">Time functions in a peculiar way within '''Level 61''', as any electronic devices will be set to the date of July 14th, 1911, though time will appear to flow normally within the level. Once any digital clocks or watches hit 12:00 AM, the date will briefly move to July 15th, 1911, before moving back to July 14th upon the next minute. All objects one retrieved within '''Level 61''' will vanish upon hitting 12:00 AM unless one exits the level. Strangely, any objects that did not originate from '''Level 61''' are unaffected by this phenomenon and will remain within one's possession no matter the amount of time spent within '''Level 61'''.</p>
</div>
<br>
<div style="text-align: center; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0); border: ridge 3.5px white; padding: 10px;>
==<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Untitled205 20240925204431.png|30px|link=]]</span> Anomalies==
<div style="text-align: center; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0); border: ridge 3.5px white; padding: 10px;>
===<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Untitled205 20240925204431.png|30px|link=]]</span> Memory Replacement and Preservation===
{{Blurimage|file=Screenshot 2025-04-16 120707-61-4.png|caption=<span style="font-family: Anuphan;">'''Another image affected by Memory Preservation.'''</span>}}
<p style="line-height:160%;">An interesting characteristic regarding '''Level 61''' is its uncanny ability to collect, preserve, and transfer memories between subjects. As one begins to spend prolonged amounts of time within '''Level 61''', symptoms similar to brain fog and lack of energy may occur, as memories are slowly extracted from one's head and replaced by new memories originating from other subjects. The degree of memory replacement increases the longer one spends with '''Level 61''', until all of one's memories are entirely replaced. Mostly complete recovery is still possible if one escapes '''Level 61''' in a timely manner, as memories are able to be gradually reintroduced upon examination of any of one's most significant objects. However, once a certain threshold is crossed, recovery is no longer possible, and subjects will not be able to retrieve their memories. Subjects affected by '''Memory Replacement''' will adopt traits such as constant personality shifts, dementia, and the forfeiting of certain learned skills one has obtained throughout their life.
</p>

<p style="line-height:160%;">Aside from '''Memory Replacement''', '''Memory Preservation''' is another related anomaly affecting photographs taken on and surrounding '''Level 61'''. Upon the cessation of any individual within '''Level 61''', all photographs taken by that individual will begin to wear down and become thicker with a texture similar to parchment paper, no matter if photos were taken within '''Level 61''' or not. One's immediate surroundings within photos will also become akin to the early 1900s, with buildings, objects, and clothes changing to match that time period. Within specific photos, facial expressions, mainly ones containing smiles, frowns, or other elements, will begin to change into a solemn, serious expression, which is theorized to take place due to the tendency to not smile within photographs taken around that time period.
</p>

</div>
<br>
<div style="text-align: center; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0); border: ridge 3.5px white; padding: 10px;>
===<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Untitled205 20240925204431.png|30px|link=]]</span> Stations===
{{Blurimage|file=Screenshot 2025-04-23 123047-61-5.png|caption=<span style="font-family: Anuphan;">'''A station within Level 61.'''</span>}}
<p style="line-height:160%;">'''Stations''' are another prevalent anomaly within '''Level 61''' manifesting as procedurally generated train platforms in which the train will stop at for a brief moment. Despite each station's seemingly outdoor nature, they are all located within an enlarged version of '''Level 61's''' tunnel, with a single oil lamp forming the "moon" of each station. Stations appear as small train platforms, always considerably lit and sterile. Each station takes on a similar appearance to train stations in the late 19th century and often possesses features such as an overhead canopy and archways/pillars supporting it.</p>

<p style="line-height:160%;">A station is usually encountered once every 6 hours within '''Level 61''', and approaching a station is marked by the tunnel widening, the appearance of foliage beside the tracks, and the fog slowly dissipating. This approach is visible no matter where one is present within '''Level 61'''. Upon arriving at a station, the train will come to a halt and open all doors, allowing access into the station itself. The train will remain in the aforementioned position for approximately five minutes before departing from the station. As the train departs from the station, it will resemble a finite train with 6-10 train cars, including a locomotive. After departure, the foliage will disappear, followed by the reemergence of fog surrounding the train itself.
</p>

<p style="line-height:160%;">Though tempting and posing the facade of a potential exit, it is advised to not exit at any station one may encounter, as upon the train's departure, the entirety of the station will begin to decrease in stability before collapsing in on itself, crushing any unfortunate individual. Afterwards, it is assumed that the remnants of the station fall into [[The Broken]] before a new section of tunnel replaces it. As of now, no one has survived a station collapse.
</p>

</div>
</div>
<br>
<div style="text-align: center; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0); border: ridge 3.5px white; padding: 10px;>
==<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Untitled205 20240925204431.png|30px|link=]]</span> Narrative==
<div style= "background:#808080; color:white; font-family:Arial; padding:15px 15px; margin:3em; text-align:left; font-size:15px">
{{Collapse|num=2|final=|body=
|initial= ===<center><span style="font-family:GFS Didot; letter-spacing:1px">13 July 1911</span></center>===
----

[[File:61Narrative1.png|thumb|350px|center]]

----
Our vacation had gone by smoothly. We did a lot of sightseeing around Rome, saw the old limestone buildings, and took a day out to the nearby beach. The kids enjoyed the trip, learning everything there was to know about Roman culture. Today will be the last day of our vacation, and tomorrow we will go back home to England. Luckily, my husband has booked something for us to do on the way home. As we exited our train leading down here on the 7th, we saw a ticket seller across the street from the station, waving a couple tickets in the air.

When we approached him, trying to know what was going on, he announced that the train company Zanetti has been dishing out free tickets for a new train route as part of a promotional offer. This route would have taken us to Milan, the same place we needed to go to transfer on the main train line towards France, where we would catch the ferry to England. All the tickets were given to members of the upper class and relatives of the railroad staff, including him and his family. However, since he and his family had important plans landing on the date of the train departure, he opted to give away the tickets for free, with the name on the tickets erased so that we could put our names in.

The ticket seller then told us of what the ride would be like. The route was specifically designed to travel through the heart of Italy's beauty, all while being accompanied by violinists and a 24/7 snack menu including a plethora of tantalizing treats and champagne. As my heart began to flutter with excitement about riding in luxury, I began to second-guess myself. Something about the ticket guy felt off, as if this was all some sort of scam. Why would he give away the tickets for a luxury tourist train completely for free? Though my husband was more than eager to ride the train, and so he snatched the tickets on the spot.

We are currently getting settled into bed. Tomorrow, we will ride the streetcar up to Rome's central station and board the train. Part of me still believes that the guy was scamming us, though who doesn't want a free train ride?

<u><center>Click to continue</center></u>
|body={{Collapse|num=3|final=
|initial= ===<center><span style="font-family:GFS Didot; letter-spacing:1px">14 July 1911</span></center>===
----

[[File:61Narrative2.png|thumb|350px|center]]

----
As we boarded, the conductor was right nearby. After getting our tickets stamped, we started making our way towards our cabin. As we walked through the aisles, I noticed that every other passenger passing us by was dressed in ornate suits and dresses with a multitude of different colors and patterns. Even though we all put on our best clothing, we all stuck out like a sore thumb, and a lot of the passengers looked at us with a curious expression, as if to analyze us.

We made it to our cabin, which was equipped with two pairs of cots, one for me and my husband, and another cot styled in a bunk bed format for the kids, each tucked in separate rooms. A smaller room to the side functioned as a bathroom, and the center room had a small desk with a chair facing it. A large window was also positioned in front of the desk, allowing picturesque views of the Italian landscape. The complexity of the cabin surprised us, as we were used to sleeping on the train seats with less than admirable passengers surrounding us during overnight trips.

I have a feeling that this is going to be an awesome end to our vacation.
<u><center>Click to continue</center></u>
|body={{Collapse|num=4|final=
|initial= ===<center><span style="font-family:GFS Didot; letter-spacing:1px">14 July... 1911?</span></center>===
----

[[File:61Narrative3.png|thumb|250px|center]]

----
Our journey is almost done. The train arrived here faster than we thought, and we only have to travel across the southern half of Lombardy before pulling into Milan. This excursion was beautiful; we saw lush landscapes and towering mountains, and a nice blue sky hung over us. The temperature was modest, and the breeze today was awesome. The kids loved sticking their hands out and feeling the wind pass by. We enjoyed the luxuries of the train itself, including the restaurant and bar car, even though many of the other passengers kept giving glances at us due to us being a middle-class family.

Though we are close to our final stop, there is one last locale along our route: a tunnel through Lombardy Mountain. The conductor informed us that we will approach the tunnel in around 10 minutes. Upon entering the tunnel, we will be immersed in darkness before reemerging in a different region, with different culture and appearances. This tunnel is supposed to be one of the longest ever built, so it will be very exciting.

<span style="text-shadow:4px -3px 0px, 2px -1.5px 0px;">I feel sad that we all have to leave Italy behind, we all wish we could stay forever.</span>

'''<span style="text-shadow:4px -3px 0px, 2px -1.5px 0px;">Though, who knows? Maybe we will be able to return another time.</span>'''

<u><center>Click to continue</center></u>
|body={{Collapse|num=5|final=
|initial=
----

[[File:61Narrative4-1.png|thumb|350px|center]]

----
Being one of the longest tunnels ever constructed for the time, the Lombardy Mountain Tunnel was a pivotal feature in engineering history. Tunneling nearly a half mile underneath Lombardy Mountain, hence its namesake, the tunnel completed a vital route within Italy's rail network, forming a faster connection between Rome and Milan through the interior of the country. The tunnel served as a landmark in the rail system, with many scenic and regular routes utilizing the tunnel at a particular point along their journey.

However, despite the tunnel's beneficial location, it had a dark secret. According to the primary principles of [[The Void|noclipping]], one is capable of entering the Backrooms itself via exploitation of unstable matter, causing objects to lose their physical barriers. This effectively opens a doorway that one can exploit to enter this forsaken realm, which closes after a set amount of time.

In the case of the Lombardy Tunnel, it happened to be located in an area containing large amounts of unstable matter tucked within the dirt and rocks making up Lombardy Mountain, opening gateways leading directly into the Backrooms itself. These gateways were only open for short periods of time, ranging from a few seconds to a few minutes. On occasion, a small pile of dirt and rocks would end up within the confines of the Backrooms, though the time frame was too short to severely displace stable matter. As a result, the concentrations of unstable matter did not affect Lombardy Mountain's overall shape or height, and locals were none the wiser.

Despite the tunnel's unstable location, construction was largely uneventful, with no anomalies ever being recorded. The limestone boring that supported the tunnel formed an effective barrier against the matter, as well as construction typically taking place when the matter was at its utmost stability. The tunnel opened in the spring of 1909, and large numbers of trains began to traverse the tunnel, connecting large population centers.

As time passed, the consequences of building a tunnel in an unstable area began to show. Holes began to appear within the tunnel's boring as a result of unstable matter slowly chewing it away. Cracks appeared as well, and anomalies began to show. Workers and train conductors utilizing the tunnel on a regular basis began realizing that the tunnel felt slightly longer when traversing it from one point to another point opposite the tunnel, and when traveling back to the initial point where they began, the time felt slightly shorter. These anomalies, although slight, served as warning signs of something more to come, and soon enough, the worst reared its ugly head.
<u><center>Click to continue</center></u>
|body={{Collapse|num=6|final=
|initial=
----

[[File:61Narrative4.5.png|thumb|350px|center]]

----
A few months preceding July 14th, 1911, a massive earthquake hit the area around Lombardy Mountain and its tunnel, causing widespread damage across surrounding areas and towns. Since the Lombardy Mountain tunnel was located near the epicenter of the earthquake, it received the brunt of the damage. Repairs commenced instantly after the earthquake, which progressed without issue in the first few days. However, the earthquake also unearthed the unstable matter present in Lombardy Mountain, causing more anomalies to show, including the disappearance of tools, equipment, and other workers. Talks about stopping repairs on the tunnel and constructing another tunnel a few miles to the east began to circulate, though the pressure from railroad companies for the faster route and the costs of building another tunnel under a strict money-saving policy overshadowed the risks, and repairs were eventually finished a full five months after the earthquake hit. The tunnel reopened in the summer of 1911, and the first month of the tunnel's reopening passed uneventfully.

However, over the course of the summer, the tunnel began to change. As a cost-cutting measure, the company began using the stone from Lombardy Mountain for the tunnel's boring, which was determined to be sturdy enough via shoddy safety tests. This went against the terms of the contract, as the company could not use any amount of rock from the mountain to preserve its shape and beauty, so it was all kept under a low profile. If anyone outside of the company itself, such as safety inspectors, figured out the truth, they would be bribed to turn a blind eye towards the situation. Any former workers who revealed the truth were also given exorbitant fees in exchange for retracting their statement, thus ensuring that no one would find out.

And it was here that a fatal flaw was made, as using the stone from Lombardy Mountain meant incorporating the unstable matter within it. Soon enough, the matter activated across the tunnel, slowly stretching and weaving a pathway across dimensions. When it was all finished, the Lombardy Tunnel became a [[Esoteric Category List|Terminal]], a bridge between the Frontrooms and the Backrooms, with no way to ever turn back.
<u><center>Click to Continue</center></u>
|body=
----

[[File:61Narrative5.png|thumb|350px|center]]

----
As a newly formed terminal, other trains were able to pass through as it was forming, albeit with many anomalies, such as varying tunnel length and non-Euclidean space. Even as the terminal was officially formed, it only led to the [[The Void|Void]], as no level was positioned at the other side of the terminal due to the instability of it.

However, the final piece would be eventually inserted, which would become the level on the other side of the Lombardy Tunnel:

The Zanetti Train.

On July 14th, 1911, the Zanetti Railway company launched a new tourist train route leading from Rome to Milan, which involved passing directly through the Lombardy Mountain Tunnel. As part of a promotional offer, Zanetti chose members from the upper class to board the train for a free ride. Tracks leading to the tunnel were closed on both ends the night before to ensure no disruptions occurred on the route. The train left the city of Rome carrying 106 passengers total, who were all eager to see what Italy had to offer. The train rolled through green pastures, high-altitude peaks, and breathtaking villages.

Soon enough, the train arrived at the Lombardy Tunnel, now a formed terminal into the Backrooms. As the train entered the tunnel, a white, milky-white fog began to envelop the train, accompanied by a plume of black smoke. The white fog entered the first car, swirling in complex patterns. As the passengers breathed in the fog, rashes began to break out across their skin, and their breathing became hampered. Shortly thereafter, they passed out, with foam pouring out of the mouth and nose area. Many passengers attempted to run and escape the fog, though the fog was too quick, and they soon joined their fellow passengers. The white fog soon spread through the middle and back carriages, where they, too, collapsed.

Sensing the situation, two passengers leaped out of the train windows just as the front car split open. Once the two passengers came to, the train was gone, dragged into another realm beyond their comprehension. Once the train fully entered the confines of the Backrooms, it filled the space on the other side of the terminal, expanding and developing anomalous properties. Eventually, the train formed a new level, the destination level for the Lombardy Tunnel, which was labeled '''Level 61''' via the [[Phenomenon 13|Casper-Bray Numbering System]]. The passengers themselves were never seen again, with many theories stating that the passengers became an anomalous entity exclusive to the level or that they were cast into the Void as the level was forming.

Once the Italian government got word of the train's disappearance, a team of investigators was sent into the Lombardy Tunnel, which reported no signs of a crash nor any signs of any of the train's passengers. Unfortunately, the investigators did not return from the tunnel and, through their radios, told the team at the tunnel's entrance that it had vanished, being replaced by more of the tunnel. The investigation team kept communications running far into the night and the next day, with their radios finally cutting off at a point approximately 60 miles south of the tunnel entrance, where they presumably noclipped into '''Level 61''' proper and die due to the level's hazards.

Following the disappearance of the investigation team, the Italian government and the company that built the Lombardy Tunnel began running cover-up stories, with families of the passengers being told that the incident was a result of building errors within the tunnel, causing the structure to collapse on the train. News was withheld from leaving Italy, and other countries did not find out about the train's disappearance until 20 years later. Shortly afterwards, a narrative about the train being an urban legend was launched, with many details being added about time travel to different eras, nonexistent families including the presumed "Sandjino Family," and a signalman within a small village in Ukraine. Official documents went through an investigation process, where anything about the Lombardy Tunnel was erased.

30 years after the Zanetti Train's disappearance, the tunnel was bombed by Allied air raids in World War II...

...sealing it off completely.
}}}}}}}}}}
